TY  - JOUR
T1  - Marx's Hypotheses on the Length of the Working Day
AU  - West, Edwin G.
Y1  - 1983/04/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261142
DO  - 10.1086/261142
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 266
EP  - 281
VL  - 91
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - In order to argue that value depends exclusively on labor, Marx had to assume a uniform rate of surplus value (exploitation) across all industries. But if this rate of exploitation is the same everywhere, hours of work have also to be uniform. Marx accordingly insisted that this was so and quoted contemporary evidence in support. A close examination of his sources (nineteenth-century factory inspectors' reports) fails, however, to confirm his prediction. Instead the data are more consistent with the competing neoclassical hypothesis, originating with Jevons, that work hours will vary because workers' labor and leisure preferences vary.
AB  - In order to argue that value depends exclusively on labor, Marx had to assume a uniform rate of surplus value (exploitation) across all industries. But if this rate of exploitation is the same everywhere, hours of work have also to be uniform. Marx accordingly insisted that this was so and quoted contemporary evidence in support. A close examination of his sources (nineteenth-century factory inspectors' reports) fails, however, to confirm his prediction. Instead the data are more consistent with the competing neoclassical hypothesis, originating with Jevons, that work hours will vary because workers' labor and leisure preferences vary.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261142
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261142
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - On Optimal Wage Indexation
AU  - Karni, Edi
Y1  - 1983/04/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261143
DO  - 10.1086/261143
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 282
EP  - 292
VL  - 91
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - The observed practice of contracting for labor services in advance introduces stickiness or friction into the economic system. In the presence of monetary and real stochastic disturbances the stability of the levels of employment and output hinges on the nature of the wage contracts. In this paper we demonstrate the existence of optimal indexation schemes that are capable of eliminating the aforementioned friction by duplicating the equilibrium that would obtain if labor services were contracted for after the stochastic disturbances were realized.
AB  - The observed practice of contracting for labor services in advance introduces stickiness or friction into the economic system. In the presence of monetary and real stochastic disturbances the stability of the levels of employment and output hinges on the nature of the wage contracts. In this paper we demonstrate the existence of optimal indexation schemes that are capable of eliminating the aforementioned friction by duplicating the equilibrium that would obtain if labor services were contracted for after the stochastic disturbances were realized.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261143
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261143
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Sex Differentials in Unemployment Rates: A Case for No Concern
AU  - Johnson, Janet L.
Y1  - 1983/04/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261144
DO  - 10.1086/261144
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 293
EP  - 303
VL  - 91
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper reevaluates the concept of unemployment in the context of differing labor market and nonmarket opportunities for men and women, discussing common fallacies in female to male unemployment rate comparisons and their use as an indicator of labor market equality. Suggestive empirical evidence is presented for an alternative unemployment rate concept for women, for interpreting the procyclical variation in female to male unemployment rate differentials, and for decomposing unemployment differences into differences in labor market characteristics and in behavioral coefficients for the two sexes. The paper concludes that a large part of the observed unemployment rate differential may be attributed to the definition and methodology used in deriving unemployment statistics rather than to discrimination in productive opportunities.
AB  - This paper reevaluates the concept of unemployment in the context of differing labor market and nonmarket opportunities for men and women, discussing common fallacies in female to male unemployment rate comparisons and their use as an indicator of labor market equality. Suggestive empirical evidence is presented for an alternative unemployment rate concept for women, for interpreting the procyclical variation in female to male unemployment rate differentials, and for decomposing unemployment differences into differences in labor market characteristics and in behavioral coefficients for the two sexes. The paper concludes that a large part of the observed unemployment rate differential may be attributed to the definition and methodology used in deriving unemployment statistics rather than to discrimination in productive opportunities.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261144
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261144
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The Interdependence of Individual Portfolio Decisions and the Demand for Insurance
AU  - Mayers, David
AU  - Smith,, Clifford W.
Y1  - 1983/04/01
PY  - 1983
DA  - 1983/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/261145
DO  - 10.1086/261145
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 304
EP  - 311
VL  - 91
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We analyze the individual's demand for insurance as a special case of general portfolio hedging activity. The demand for insurance contracts is determined simultaneously with the demands for other assets in the portfolio. We demonstrate that when the payoffs of the policy are correlated with the payoffs to the individual's other assets, the demand for insurance contracts is generally not a separable portfolio decision. We argue that this separability condition is not generally met because of significant interdependence of claims across different insurance policies. Furthermore, our generalizations can reverse the standard prediction that wealthier individuals will demand less insurance.
AB  - We analyze the individual's demand for insurance as a special case of general portfolio hedging activity. The demand for insurance contracts is determined simultaneously with the demands for other assets in the portfolio. We demonstrate that when the payoffs of the policy are correlated with the payoffs to the individual's other assets, the demand for insurance contracts is generally not a separable portfolio decision. We argue that this separability condition is not generally met because of significant interdependence of claims across different insurance policies. Furthermore, our generalizations can reverse the standard prediction that wealthier individuals will demand less insurance.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/261145
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/261145
Y2  - 2024/03/22
ER  - 

